/* ---------------- 2.1 Convex sets & convex functions ---------------- */
window.ALLML_CONTENT["2.1"] = {
  tagline: "Convexity is the promise that straight-line mixtures behave: feasible mixtures stay feasible, and function chords stay above the graph.",
  colab: "https://colab.research.google.com/github/niamleeson/ml-math/blob/main/notebooks/2.1-convex-sets-functions.ipynb",
  context: String.raw`<p>Convexity is the language that makes optimization trustworthy.</p><ul><li><b>Linear algebra</b> supplies vectors and weighted sums; a convex combination is literally a weighted vector average.</li><li><b>Calculus</b> supplies slopes and curvature; the second derivative or Hessian becomes the local certificate for convex functions.</li><li><b>Probability</b> contributes expectations, because Jensen's inequality is convexity applied to weighted averages.</li></ul><p>Where it leads: optimality conditions in (2.2), gradient descent guarantees in (2.3), Newton methods in (2.5), and duality in (2.10) all become clean because convex problems have no deceptive local minima.</p>`,
  intuition: String.raw`<p>The concrete problem is simple: we want a landscape where moving downhill locally does not lead us into a false valley. Nonconvex sets can contain holes, and nonconvex functions can hide traps; local reasoning then becomes fragile.</p><p>The mental model is a bowl and a solid room. In a convex set, the straight string between any two feasible points never leaves the room. In a convex function, the straight chord between two graph points never dips below the bowl.</p><p>The design decision people gloss over is why we care about straight-line mixtures instead of arbitrary curves. Optimization algorithms make local linear and quadratic models; if straight-line interpolation is safe, those local models can be turned into global statements.</p>`,
  mathematics: String.raw`<p>A set $C\subseteq\mathbb{R}^d$ is convex when $\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y\in C$ for all $x,y\in C$ and $0\le\lambda\le1$. A function $f:C	o\mathbb{R}$ is convex when $f(\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y)\le\lambda f(x)+(1-\lambda)f(y)$.</p><p><b>A convex combination.</b></p><ol class="work"><li>$x=(0,0)$, $y=(2,1)$, $\lambda=0.25$</li><li>$0.25x+0.75y=(0,0)+(1.5,0.75)=(1.5,0.75)$</li><li>The point lies inside the square $[0,2]^2$.</li></ol><p>The numbers show feasibility is preserved by averaging, which is exactly why convex constraints are stable under interpolation.</p><p><b>Jensen on $f(x)=x^2$.</b></p><ol class="work"><li>$0.25\cdot1+0.75\cdot3=2.5$</li><li>$f(2.5)=2.5^2=6.25$</li><li>$0.25f(1)+0.75f(3)=0.25\cdot1+0.75\cdot9=7.00$</li><li>$6.25\le7.00$</li></ol><p>The function value at the average is lower than the average function value; that is the algebraic shape of a bowl.</p><p><b>Second-order certificate.</b> For $f(x)=x^2$, $f''(x)=2\gt0$, so every tangent is a global lower bound. At $x_0=2$, the tangent is $4+4(x-2)$.</p><ol class="work"><li>At $x=3$, tangent $=4+4(1)=8$</li><li>Function $=3^2=9$</li><li>$9\ge8$</li></ol><p>That one-sided support is what later lets gradients certify optimality.</p>`,
  pitfalls: String.raw`<ul><li><b>Confusing connected with convex.</b> A ring is connected, but the midpoint of opposite points falls in the hole, violating the combination formula.</li><li><b>Checking only endpoints.</b> Convexity is about every $\lambda\in[0,1]$, not just the two original points.</li><li><b>Assuming smoothness.</b> A function like $|x|$ is convex without a derivative at zero; subgradients in (2.8) handle the corner.</li></ul>`
};

