/* ---------------- 2.10 Duality (Lagrangian & Wolfe) ---------------- */
window.ALLML_CONTENT["2.10"] = {
  tagline: "Duality turns constraints into prices and asks how strong a certificate those prices can prove.",
  colab: "https://colab.research.google.com/github/niamleeson/ml-math/blob/main/notebooks/2.10-duality.ipynb",
  context: String.raw`<p>This lesson is the certificate view of constrained optimization.</p><ul><li><b>KKT multipliers (2.9)</b> become the variables of the dual problem.</li><li><b>Convexity (2.1)</b> is what often closes the gap between primal and dual.</li><li><b>Linear and quadratic programs (2.12)</b> are the cleanest places to see dual certificates in action.</li></ul><p>Where it leads: SVM duals, regularization paths, constrained learning, and sensitivity analysis all rely on the same multiplier-price interpretation.</p>`,
  intuition: String.raw`<p>The concrete problem is proving optimality. Finding a feasible point gives an upper bound for minimization; the dual gives a lower bound. When the two meet, the proof is complete.</p><p>The mental model is negotiation. The primal chooses variables; the dual chooses prices for constraint violations. Bad prices prove weak bounds, good prices reveal the true optimum.</p><p>The design decision is to minimize the Lagrangian over primal variables first. That produces a bound that is valid for every feasible primal point, which is why weak duality is so reliable.</p>`,
  mathematics: String.raw`<p>For primal minimize $f(x)$ subject to $g(x)\le0$, the Lagrangian is $L(x,\mu)=f(x)+\mu g(x)$ with $\mu\ge0$. The dual function is $q(\mu)=\inf_x L(x,\mu)$, and weak duality says $q(\mu)\le p^\star$.</p><p><b>A lower bound.</b> Minimize $x^2$ subject to $x\ge1$, with $g(x)=1-x$.</p><ol class="work"><li>$L(x,1)=x^2+1-x$</li><li>Derivative $2x-1=0$, so $x=0.5$</li><li>$q(1)=0.25+1-0.5=0.75$</li></ol><p>The true constrained value is $1$, and $0.75$ is a valid lower bound.</p><p><b>Best multiplier.</b></p><ol class="work"><li>For general $\mu$, minimize $x^2+\mu(1-x)$ at $x=\mu/2$</li><li>$q(\mu)=\mu-\mu^2/4$</li><li>Derivative $1-\mu/2=0$ gives $\mu=2$</li><li>$q(2)=2-4/4=1$</li></ol><p>The lower bound meets the primal value, so the certificate is exact.</p><p><b>A gap example.</b> If an integer constraint leaves primal value $1$ but the relaxation proves only $0$, the gap is $1-0=1$.</p>`,
  pitfalls: String.raw`<ul><li><b>Maximizing the Lagrangian over $x$ for a minimization problem.</b> The dual function uses an infimum, because it must be a lower bound.</li><li><b>Assuming strong duality everywhere.</b> Weak duality is automatic; zero gap needs convexity and regularity conditions.</li><li><b>Interpreting multipliers without units.</b> A multiplier prices one unit of constraint tightening, so scaling the constraint rescales the multiplier.</li></ul>`
};

