  context: String.raw`<p>This lesson studies two optimization families whose structure is strong enough for dependable solvers.</p><ul><li><b>Convex sets (2.1)</b> appear as polytopes defined by linear inequalities.</li><li><b>KKT (2.9)</b> explains active constraints and multipliers at the solution.</li><li><b>Duality (2.10)</b> gives certificates for LP and QP optima.</li></ul><p>Where it leads: SVMs, portfolio optimization, resource allocation, scheduling relaxations, and many ML subroutines are LPs or QPs.</p>`,
  intuition: String.raw`<p>The concrete problem is optimizing with linear rules. If the objective is linear, level sets slide until they touch a corner. If the objective is quadratic, a bowl is clipped by feasible walls.</p><p>The mental model is light shining across a polygon. A linear objective chooses the last illuminated vertex; a quadratic objective drops a point onto the feasible region like a projection.</p><p>The design decision is preserving linear constraints. Their geometry lets solvers reason through vertices, active sets, and dual certificates rather than blind search.</p>`,
  mathematics: String.raw`<p>An LP has form maximize $c^Tx$ subject to $Ax\le b$. A convex QP has form minimize $	frac12x^THx+c^Tx$ subject to linear constraints, with $H\succeq0$.</p><p><b>LP vertex arithmetic.</b> Feasible vertices are $(0,0)$, $(2,0)$, and $(0,1)$; objective $c=(1,2)$.</p><ol class="work"><li>$c^T(0,0)=0$</li><li>$c^T(2,0)=2$</li><li>$c^T(0,1)=2$</li></ol><p>The optimum is attained at a vertex; here two vertices tie, reminding us LP optima need not be unique.</p><p><b>Active constraint for projection.</b> Project $p=(2,2)$ onto $x+2y\le2$ with closest point $(0.4,0.8)$.</p><ol class="work"><li>Feasibility: $0.4+2(0.8)=2.0$</li><li>Squared distance: $(2-0.4)^2+(2-0.8)^2=1.6^2+1.2^2=2.56+1.44=4.00$</li></ol><p>The quadratic objective lands on the active edge because the unconstrained point is infeasible.</p><p><b>Equality QP.</b> Minimize $	frac12\|x\|^2$ subject to $x_1+x_2=1$.</p><ol class="work"><li>By symmetry $x_1=x_2=0.5$</li><li>Objective $=0.5(0.25+0.25)=0.25$</li></ol><p>The minimum-norm feasible point splits mass evenly across identical coordinates.</p>`,
  pitfalls: String.raw`<ul><li><b>Expecting interior LP optima.</b> A nonconstant linear objective over a polytope optimizes on the boundary, often at a vertex.</li><li><b>Using QP solvers with indefinite $H$.</b> Convex guarantees require $H\succeq0$; negative curvature turns the problem nonconvex.</li><li><b>Ignoring degeneracy.</b> Tied vertices or redundant constraints can make multipliers nonunique even when the optimal value is clear.</li></ul>`
