  context: String.raw`<p>This lesson leaves the smooth world.</p><ul><li><b>LP relaxations (2.12)</b> provide bounds by allowing fractional choices.</li><li><b>Duality (2.10)</b> explains why bounds can certify pruning even before an integer solution is found.</li><li><b>Black-box and metaheuristic methods (2.15, 2.16)</b> become useful when exact combinatorial search is too large.</li></ul><p>Where it leads: feature selection, routing, assignment, model compression, and scheduling all contain discrete decisions.</p>`,
  intuition: String.raw`<p>The concrete problem is choosing among combinations: which items, which assignment, which route. The feasible set is not a bowl; it is a constellation of isolated points.</p><p>The naive continuous instinct says to relax the variables and round. Sometimes that works, but the fractional solution can be better than any legal integer solution, creating an integrality gap.</p><p>The design decision is how to combine search with bounds. Branch-and-bound explores discrete choices while relaxations prove that some branches cannot beat the incumbent.</p>`,
  mathematics: String.raw`<p>A 0-1 integer program uses variables $z_j\in\{0,1\}$. A knapsack maximizes $v^Tz$ subject to $w^Tz\le C$.</p><p><b>Knapsack enumeration.</b> Weights $(2,3,4)$, values $(3,4,5)$, capacity $5$.</p><ol class="work"><li>Choose items 1 and 2: weight $2+3=5$, value $3+4=7$</li><li>Choose item 3 only: weight $4$, value $5$</li><li>Choose items 1 and 3: weight $6\gt5$, infeasible</li></ol><p>The best legal discrete choice is $(1,1,0)$ with value $7$.</p><p><b>Relaxation gap.</b> In a two-item knapsack with weights $(4,5)$, values $(7,10)$, and capacity $6$, the best integer choice is item 2 with value $10$.</p><ol class="work"><li>Take item 2 fully: weight $5$, value $10$</li><li>Use the remaining capacity for $0.25$ of item 1: extra weight $0.25\cdot4=1$, extra value $0.25\cdot7=1.75$</li><li>Fractional value $=10+1.75=11.75$</li><li>Gap $=11.75-10=1.75$</li></ol><p>The fractional bound is useful for pruning, but it is not itself a legal answer.</p><p><b>Assignment enumeration.</b> Cost matrix $egin{bmatrix}4&1&3\2&0&5\3&2&2\end{bmatrix}$.</p><ol class="work"><li>Assignment $(1,0,2)$ costs $1+2+2=5$</li><li>Assignment $(0,1,2)$ costs $4+0+2=6$</li></ol><p>The combinatorial constraint is one job per row and column; the arithmetic is easy only because the example is tiny.</p>`,
  pitfalls: String.raw`<ul><li><b>Rounding without checking feasibility.</b> Fractional LP variables satisfy relaxed constraints, not necessarily integer constraints.</li><li><b>Misreading bounds as solutions.</b> A branch bound can prove impossibility but does not provide a feasible incumbent.</li><li><b>Ignoring symmetry.</b> Equivalent discrete configurations multiply the search tree unless the formulation breaks or exploits symmetry.</li></ul>`
