  intuition: String.raw`<p>The concrete problem is choosing the next experiment when each experiment is slow or costly. Random search wastes evaluations; greedy search gets trapped by early lucky observations.</p><p>The mental model is a map with fog. The surrogate mean marks promising valleys, while posterior uncertainty marks places the map is still blank. The acquisition function decides where information is worth buying.</p><p>The design decision is not to optimize the surrogate mean directly. We optimize an acquisition function, because the next point should be valuable either by looking good or by reducing important uncertainty.</p>`,
  mathematics: String.raw`<p>Bayesian optimization keeps data $D=\{(x_i,y_i)\}$, a surrogate posterior with mean $\mu(x)$ and standard deviation $\sigma(x)$, and an acquisition such as UCB $a(x)=\mu(x)+\kappa\sigma(x)$ for maximization.</p><p><b>Posterior interpolation.</b> With observations $(0,0),(1,1),(2,0)$ and a narrow RBF kernel, the posterior mean near $x=1$ is about $1.000$.</p><ol class="work"><li>Observed value at $x=1$ is $1$</li><li>Kernel self-similarity at the observed point dominates neighboring terms</li><li>Posterior mean $\mu(1)pprox1.000$</li></ol><p>The surrogate honors data while smoothing between observations.</p><p><b>Expected improvement ingredients.</b> If current best is $1.0$, a candidate has $\mu=0.8$ and $\sigma=0.3$:</p><ol class="work"><li>$z=(0.8-1.0)/0.3=-0.6667$</li><li>$\Phi(z)=0.2525$, $\phi(z)=0.3194$</li><li>$EI=(-0.2)(0.2525)+0.3(0.3194)=0.0453$</li></ol><p>Even a below-best mean can be worth sampling if uncertainty leaves upside.</p><p><b>UCB knob.</b> If $\mu=0.6$ and $\sigma=0.2$:</p><ol class="work"><li>$\kappa=0.5$: $a=0.6+0.5(0.2)=0.7$</li><li>$\kappa=2$: $a=0.6+2(0.2)=1.0$</li></ol><p>Larger $\kappa$ pays more for uncertainty and therefore explores more aggressively.</p>`,
  pitfalls: String.raw`<ul><li><b>Optimizing the posterior mean alone.</b> That removes the exploration term $\sigma(x)$ and can overcommit to early data.</li><li><b>Using a poor kernel silently.</b> The surrogate's covariance encodes smoothness; a mismatched kernel makes uncertainty misleading.</li><li><b>Forgetting observation noise.</b> Noisy evaluations should not be interpolated as exact truths unless the model includes a noise term.</li></ul>`
